 the Islamic Legal Tradition -- tʿAlī’s Contemplations on this World and the Hereafter in the Context of His Life and Times -- tPart IV: Islamic History and Historiography -- tAl-ʿAṭṭāf b. Sufyān and Abbasid Imperialism -- tAn Early Arabic Conversion Story: The Case of al-Faḍl b. Sahl -- tA Translation of the Prolegomena to Żiyāʾ al-Dīn Baranī’s Tārīkh-i Fīrūzshāhī -- tIndex of Names -- tIndex of Geographical Places0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe articles in this volume are dedicated to Professor Ahmad Mahdavi Damghani for the breadth and depth of his interests and his influence on those interests. They attest to the fact that his fervor and rigorously surgical attention to detail have found fertile ground in a wide variety of disciplines, including (among others) Persian literature and philology; Islamic history and historiography; Arabic literature and philology; and Islamic philosophy and jurisprudence. The volume has brought together some of the most respected scholars in the fields of Islamic studies and Islamic literatures, all his prior students, to contribute with articles that touch on the fields Professor Mahdavi Damghani has so permanently touched with his astonishing scholarship and attention to detail.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 4aIslam Studies. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aArabic studies.  aIslam studies.  aPersian studies.1 aAuer, Blain, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBassiri, Kambiz Ghanea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrustad, Kristen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClarke, Lynda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCooperson, Michae